<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="3d5686a5-b6bb-5713-9017-2dffce8cf98e" activityNameId="1f17045b-bab7-42d0-be15-bfefc0014621" parentActivityId="2db4881f-9141-4e05-bc96-07c6948d33c7" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">maleic anhydride production by catalytic oxidation of benzene</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Maleic acid anhydride</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> 2,5-Furandione</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> Toxilic anhydride</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> 108-31-6</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> Furan-2,5-dione</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity ends with the production of maleic anhydride, with steam as a byproduct. All precursors and infrastructure are included.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of maleic anhydride, with steam as by product. Maleic anhydride is an organic chemical compound which consists of white crystalline flakes that have a pungent, acrid odor. It is soluble in acetone, ether and petroleum. According to (IPPC Chemicals, 2002), maleic anhydride is used to produce unsaturated polyesters, fumaric and maleic acid, and is also used as an intermediate for the production of pesticides.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">In 1991, one-third of maleic acid production capacity was based on benzene oxidation and the rest was from the oxidation of butane and butene. Notably, the n-butane pathway is classified as the most economic raw material for maleic anhydride production. Thereofe, n-butane is the preferred pathway in the US and Japan, while existing facilities were converted to accept C4 feedstocks instead of benzene. Major manufacturers include Lonza, Bayer and Huntsman, among many others (Wells, 1999).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Maleic anhydride reacts with water to form maleic acid and will dimerize in the presence of UV light. A decomposition/polymerization reaction will occur with alkalis at elevated temperatures. It is a skin, eye and mucous membrane irritant (Wells, 1999).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">In this dataset, the raw material inputs, and process-specific material exchanges, are modelled with a generic stoichiometry-based tool, using literature or estimated yields. The emissions are modelled with a default value, which is estimated based on losses, unreacted chemicals, among others. At the same time, the energy consumption is based on data from personal communications and literature sources. Finally, the auxiliary (i.e., cooling water and infrastructure) exchanges are modelled with a default value based on industry data from literature sources. For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Althaus H.-J., Chudacoff M., Hischier R., Jungbluth N., Osses M. and Primas A. (2007) Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals. ecoinvent report No. 8, v2.0. EMPA Dübendorf, Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Personal communication, Giovanni.Montiglio, Lonza, May 2003</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">G. Margaret Wells, “Handbook of Petrochemicals and Processes”, 2nd edition, Ashgate, 1999</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0723d252-7e2a-11de-9820-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RER</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inventory is modelled for Europe. The main material inputs and outputs of this activity are generated with on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields. Furthermore, the source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The dataset could also be considered as not geography-specific, and thus, valid for a broader geographical coverage.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chauvel, Alain, Gilles Lefebvre, and L. Castex in "Petrochemical processes. Technical and economical characteristics Vol. 2." (1989)</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="4">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Air is preheated and compressed and mixed with benzene over a catalyst Heat from the strongly process exothermic serves to produce steam (molten salts are used to remove heat). The exit gases contain maleic anhydride, carbon monoxide, carbon dioxide and traces of aromatics. 50-60% of the anhydride is obtained directly from the reaction gas mixture. The remainder is recovered in the form of maleic acid. The maleic acid is then converted to anhydride via dehydration, usually by distillation with xylene (Falcke et al., 2017). Off gases leaving the scrubber are sent to a catalytic incinerator (personal communication Lonza).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">C6H6 + 4½ O2 -&gt; C4H2O3 + H2O + 2 CO2</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">The reaction occurs at slightly elevated pressure and temperatures of 350 – 450 °C and 1.5–2.5 bar with residence times over the catalysts of about 0.1 s and an air excess. The oxidation reaction in modern plants is performed at higher concentrations of benzene in air, reducing the amount of air required by the process. This reduces the amount of electricity needed for the air compressor, which is the larger portion of the overall electricity consumption, according (personal communication Lonza).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Regarding the catalytic system, vanadium oxides are used on different promoters such as phosphorus and the oxides of Fe, Cr, Ti, Co, Ni, Mo (such as V2O5-H3PO4).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">In this dataset, a yield of 88% was assumed, according to Wells (1999). The treated exhaust gas contains undreacted benzene and carbon monoxide, and thus, is being combusted. Please note that the catalytic system is not covered.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Althaus H.-J., Chudacoff M., Hischier R., Jungbluth N., Osses M. and Primas A. (2007) Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals. ecoinvent report No. 8, v2.0. EMPA Dübendorf, Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">G. Margaret Wells, “Handbook of Petrochemicals and Processes”, 2nd edition, Ashgate, 1999</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Falcke, Heino, et al. "Best Available Techniques (BAT) reference document for the production of large volume organic chemicals." Publications Office of the European Union: Luxembourg (2017).</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="1999-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The time period spans from the earliest year from which at least one of the input values was obtained until 2022, but overall form the most realistic picture of the production. Besides, the activity is partly generated, in terms of material inputs and outputs, based on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields, which does not expect to change over time.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data (from 2007) for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park. The values are a 5-year average of data from 2015-2019 published by the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2462760. The end time period is therefore set based on the years from Gendorf reference.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure and in the comments of the exchanges.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Althaus H.-J., Chudacoff M., Hischier R., Jungbluth N., Osses M. and Primas A. (2007) Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals. ecoinvent report No. 8, v2.0. EMPA Dübendorf, Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
